        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1664915610" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8092904152668395927">It took me a while to get into this book, the first part is a bit slow and I couldn&apos;t feel aligned with the author&apos;s (or translator) rhythm. But I am glad I persevered because this book brings to life the early divisions of the Christian churches in the East and West which influenced the way Christianity was then practiced.<br/>The time is in the 430ADs. The narrator Hypa is a naive Egyptian monk who is well read, has medical training. He seeks a peaceful life and truth in religion. He experiences fi</span>
  <span id="freeText8092904152668395927" style="display:none">It took me a while to get into this book, the first part is a bit slow and I couldn't feel aligned with the author's (or translator) rhythm. But I am glad I persevered because this book brings to life the early divisions of the Christian churches in the East and West which influenced the way Christianity was then practiced.<br />The time is in the 430ADs. The narrator Hypa is a naive Egyptian monk who is well read, has medical training. He seeks a peaceful life and truth in religion. He experiences first-hand the way Cyril the Bishop of Alexander allows the murder of pagans and heretics to enable only those who practice Christianity in his interpretation. One of his arguments was that Mary should be known as the bearer of God. Hypa is more drawn to Nestorius, the Bishop of Constantinople who argues Mary should be known as Constantinople.<br />But what is behind these theological arguments is greed and a desire for power, as the Nestorius said "Killing people in the name of religion does not make it religious".<br />The book also is surprising in it's scenes of erotism, great dialogues between Hypa and Azazeel (the devil that resides with Hypa) and the recognition of the callous way Christian doctrine and practices were implemented from a very early period.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8092904152668395927" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


