  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1359278442" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1359278442" />
    <a title="Yomna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21815081-yomna"><img alt="Yomna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507912810p2/21815081.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1359278442?book_show_action=true">Aug 09, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Yomna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Yomna" href="/user/show/21815081-yomna">Yomna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1359278442" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16219058931638761559">It certainly isn&apos;t a typical book. I&apos;m used to reading books with tailored plots and explicitly jammed up events, but this one was simply the record of the life of a monk suffering from contradictory thoughts. If I call his thoughts contradictory I might be humiliating him because the state of confusion roaming around Hypa was nothing close to mediocre. He had his own reservations about his religion, Christianity, due to all the action taking place around him. He didn&apos;t know what&apos;s true and what</span>
  <span id="freeText16219058931638761559" style="display:none">It certainly isn't a typical book. I'm used to reading books with tailored plots and explicitly jammed up events, but this one was simply the record of the life of a monk suffering from contradictory thoughts. If I call his thoughts contradictory I might be humiliating him because the state of confusion roaming around Hypa was nothing close to mediocre. He had his own reservations about his religion, Christianity, due to all the action taking place around him. He didn't know what's true and what's not. If you remove the whole religion thing from the book you'll find out such resemblance between the acts that you and all the people surrounding you go through and how Hypa felt. And what he felt can only be described in one word: helplessness. Such an awful captivating word. He surrendered to all the forces of the universe when his father was killed infront of him, when his mother married one of the men who killed his father, when he moved to Alexandria and met Octavia's insane passion, when he chose to discontinue Hypatia's ..... and so on. I can continue listing all the things he chose not to take an action against and you'll figure out at the end that he hadn't stood up against anything. We all have our doubts and we all get these self loathing moments, just like Hypa but on a minor scale maybe? <br /><br />In a psychological point of view though, I find Hypa's self-resentment is due to the fact that being a monk denies you from basic life desires and needs which only generates more lust. Once he gets the opportunity to satisfy his lust, he's left with nothing but guilt. <br /><br />I loved how this book allowed me travel into a time where Christianity was dominating and marvel at historical events from a monk's point of view. It also gave me the chance to know more about this religion and about the conflicts that gave rise to its different versions.<br /><br />The book also stated quite vividly how religion extremists should not be considered the front face of a certain religion. <br />No one can guarantee the authenticity of the book though, but as a whole even if the monk's story might be fiddled with to a certain degree, I can assure you that this book is worth reading. <br /><br />Favourite character: Hypatia! </span>
  <a data-text-id="16219058931638761559" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

