    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_718943890" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/718943890" />
    <a title="Marvin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2582387-marvin"><img alt="Marvin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1254414189p2/2582387.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/718943890?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marvin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marvin" href="/user/show/2582387-marvin">Marvin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781848874275" href="/book/show/7829608-azazeel">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2582387-marvin?shelf=religion">religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer718943890" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13890005504480782640">What an unusual, if not unique, premise for a contemporary novel! In the first third of the 5th century, an intellectually curious, troubled Christian monk/physician/poet travels from his native Upper Egypt to Alexandria, then to Jerusalem (where he meets and becomes intimate friends with Nestorius before he becomes bishop of Constantinople) before settling in a monastery near Aleppo. The Nestorian controversy serves as a backdrop for the story, but the monk narrates his adventures as an intimat</span>
  <span id="freeText13890005504480782640" style="display:none">What an unusual, if not unique, premise for a contemporary novel! In the first third of the 5th century, an intellectually curious, troubled Christian monk/physician/poet travels from his native Upper Egypt to Alexandria, then to Jerusalem (where he meets and becomes intimate friends with Nestorius before he becomes bishop of Constantinople) before settling in a monastery near Aleppo. The Nestorian controversy serves as a backdrop for the story, but the monk narrates his adventures as an intimate autobiography in conversation with Azazeel (Satan). The formal, pious style, evoking 5th-century piety, takes some getting used to, but the monk is such an endearing character that I was thoroughly taken in to his life--and his questions. Whole paragraphs are strings of questions about things he wonders about, many of which would never occur to us to wonder about: Where do the worms come from that consume dead flesh? Who is Azazeel (Satan)? "I wonder if the Lord dreams. Who knows? For maybe this universe with everything in it is just on of His dreams" (191). Not surprisingly for a contemporary novel, the narrator is deeply troubled by the violence engaged in by Christians in their attempts to enforce orthodoxy and punish what they define as heresy. All in all, it's an engaging, fascinating story, though with all the arcane theology and piety at the heart of it, I'm amazed that nearly 18,000 GoodReads readers have discovered this book. (I had to get it on interlibrary loan from the University of Oklahoma Library.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="13890005504480782640" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


