<div id="review_3122044226" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3122044226" />
    <a title="Detective Deralta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46848445-detective-deralta"><img alt="Detective Deralta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469777927p2/46848445.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3122044226?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Detective Deralta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Detective Deralta" href="/user/show/46848445-detective-deralta">Detective Deralta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781848874275" href="/book/show/7829608-azazeel">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3122044226" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9987012054141483066">An utterly absorbing fiction that takes you on a journey of first 500years of Christianity in Egypt, through the narrative of a Coptic monk. Egypt doesn’t feature immediately in our collective psyche as a Christian country and therefore the impact isn’t immediately relatable but that’s also what makes more interesting and impact. The book is fictional but it weaves factual incidents and characters so beautifully you’d think it is a real scroll that’s been translated. Kudos to the translator and </span>
  <span id="freeText9987012054141483066" style="display:none">An utterly absorbing fiction that takes you on a journey of first 500years of Christianity in Egypt, through the narrative of a Coptic monk. Egypt doesn’t feature immediately in our collective psyche as a Christian country and therefore the impact isn’t immediately relatable but that’s also what makes more interesting and impact. The book is fictional but it weaves factual incidents and characters so beautifully you’d think it is a real scroll that’s been translated. Kudos to the translator and writer. <br /><br />The book is a fun read if you like a bit of history, geography. It compelled me to google names of people and places, churches. Made me want to travel to Egypt too to look at it from a different lens. <br /><br />It’s also a discourse on ideas of good and evil, of love and lust, of god and its creations. If you look, it will also show how progress of one religion has been at the suppression, killing, torture and tormenting of previous ones. How power prevents dissent, debates, discussions just so it can reign supreme. In that sense, it makes sense across millennia and not just the times it’s set in. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9987012054141483066" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


